class Solution {
public:
    int paintWalls(vector<int>& cost, vector<int>& time) {
        int n = cost.size();
        vector<int> f(n * 2 + 1, INT_MAX / 2);
        f[n] = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            vector<int> g(n * 2 + 1, INT_MAX / 2);
            for (int j = 0; j <= n * 2; ++j) {
                // 付费
                g[j] = min(g[j], f[j] + cost[i]);
                // 免费
                if (j > 0) {
                    g[j - 1] = min(g[j - 1], f[j]);
                }
            }
            f = move(g);
        }
        return *min_element(f.begin() + n, f.end());
    }
};
```

This code uses dynamic programming to solve the problem. The `f` array represents the minimum cost to paint `i` walls, where `i` is the index of the `f` array minus `n`. The `g` array is used to update the `f` array in each iteration. For each wall, the paid painter is used, which increases the cost and decreases the time. If the free painter is available (`j > 0`), it is used to paint the wall, which does not increase the cost but decreases the time. The minimum cost of painting all walls is then returned.

